{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_0142At9PZ6JZ4ihBYoVWQ7aT","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good - the head started successfully. The Ray version on the client is 2.9.0 (same as the head), so no version mismatch.\n\nThe error is: `Can't find a node_ip_address.json file from /tmp/ray/session_...` - this means that when the client pod calls `ray.init(address='ray-head:6379')`, it tries to start local Ray processes on the client pod itself (not just connect to the head). The issue is that these local processes are failing to write `node_ip_address.json`.\n\nActually, let me look at this differently. In Ray 2.x, when you call `ray.init(address='ray-head:6379')`, it connects to the existing cluster as a \"driver\" process. This involves:\n1. Connecting to GCS at ray-head:6379\n2. Starting a local raylet process on the client pod\n3. The local raylet registers with GCS\n\nThe `node_ip_address.json` file is written by the local raylet during startup, so if the raylet fails to start properly—whether due to permissions, network issues, or other constraints—this file won't be created and the connection fails.\n\nLooking at the head logs, I see a warning about processes not registering with GCS, which suggests the local raylet on the client pod is trying to register but failing. The core issue appears to be that when `ray.init(address='ray-head:6379')` is called, the local raylet process isn't successfully starting or registering with the head node's GCS.\n\nI'm noticing the head pod is also showing a shared memory constraint warning, which could be affecting the client pod similarly. The client might be hitting resource limitations or security constraints that prevent the local raylet from starting properly. Let me examine how the client pod is configured and what's happening during the connection attempt.\n\nActually, I'm realizing the distinction here: `ray.init(address='ray-head:6379')` is meant for processes already running inside the cluster, but when called from a client pod outside the cluster, it requires the local raylet to start and connect to the GCS. The error about the missing `node_ip_address.json` file suggests the raylet process isn't initializing correctly on the client side. I need to examine the ray-client pod configuration to see what resources and settings it has, and also verify whether the worker nodes are actually connecting to the head node properly.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2788,"cache_read_input_tokens":31750,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2788},"output_tokens":18,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a5da96d4-3bc6-4961-9a3e-cea870518173","uuid":"51e88714-43ac-4b57-904d-6dc7d93d65b2","request_id":"req_011CcMkBYZNXCyQ7q1A2j7ux"}
